---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Time Scales and Time Systems">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/timing">Timing</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Time Scales</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Timing · Article 2 of 5</span>
        <h1>Time Scales and Time Systems</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          GPS time, GLONASS time, Galileo time, BeiDou time, UTC, TAI and UT1 — each GNSS
          constellation runs on its own time scale, and none of them are quite the same.
          Converting between them correctly is essential for multi-constellation processing,
          precise timing applications, and understanding why your receiver shows a different
          time than your phone.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#tai">TAI — the atomic foundation</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ut1">UT1 — Earth rotation time</a></li>
          <li><a href="#utc">UTC — the civil compromise</a></li>
          <li><a href="#leap-seconds">Leap seconds</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gnss-time-scales">GNSS time scales</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gps-time">GPS time in detail</a></li>
          <li><a href="#week-rollover">GPS week rollover</a></li>
          <li><a href="#conversions">Conversion reference</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="tai">TAI — the atomic foundation</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>International Atomic Time (TAI)</strong> — Temps Atomique International — is the
        most precise continuous time scale in existence. It is computed by the Bureau International
        des Poids et Mesures (BIPM) in Paris from the weighted average of more than 400 atomic
        clocks operated by national metrology laboratories around the world.
      </p>
      <p>
        TAI ticks at exactly the SI second — defined since 1967 as 9,192,631,770 oscillations
        of the caesium-133 hyperfine transition. It has no discontinuities, no leap seconds
        and no corrections for Earth's rotation. It is the bedrock on which all other precise
        time scales are built.
      </p>

      <div class="tai-fact">
        <div class="tf-val">~400</div>
        <div class="tf-label">atomic clocks contributing to TAI</div>
        <div class="tf-val">~70</div>
        <div class="tf-label">national labs in 30+ countries</div>
        <div class="tf-val">&lt;1 ns</div>
        <div class="tf-label">TAI accuracy (uncertainty in the SI second)</div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="ut1">UT1 — Earth rotation time</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>UT1</strong> (Universal Time 1) is a measure of Earth's actual rotation angle
        relative to distant quasars. It is what astronomers historically meant by "time" —
        the position of the Sun in the sky. UT1 is not uniform: Earth's rotation rate varies
        slightly due to tidal braking, atmospheric and oceanic angular momentum changes, and
        core-mantle coupling.
      </p>
      <p>
        The difference between UT1 and TAI (called ΔT) grows over time as Earth's rotation
        slows. Currently ΔT ≈ 69 seconds, meaning Earth's rotation is running ~69 seconds
        behind atomic time accumulated since 1958. UT1 is monitored by the International
        Earth Rotation and Reference Systems Service (IERS) using VLBI, GPS and laser ranging.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="utc">UTC — the civil compromise</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Coordinated Universal Time (UTC)</strong> is the practical compromise between
        atomic time precision (TAI) and astronomical time (UT1). It ticks at exactly the
        atomic second rate (like TAI) but is kept within 0.9 seconds of UT1 by the occasional
        insertion of <strong>leap seconds</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="timescale-relationships">
        <div class="tsr-title">Relationships between time scales</div>
        <div class="tsr-chain">
          <div class="tsr-node tsr-tai">
            <div class="tsr-name">TAI</div>
            <div class="tsr-desc">Atomic seconds, continuous, no corrections</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tsr-arrow">
            <div class="tsr-offset">−37 s (leap seconds)</div>
            <div class="tsr-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tsr-node tsr-utc">
            <div class="tsr-name">UTC</div>
            <div class="tsr-desc">Civil time standard, kept near UT1 by leap seconds</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tsr-arrow">
            <div class="tsr-offset">≤ 0.9 s (variable)</div>
            <div class="tsr-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tsr-node tsr-ut1">
            <div class="tsr-name">UT1</div>
            <div class="tsr-desc">Earth rotation, irregular, slowing over time</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="leap-seconds">Leap seconds</h2>
      <p>
        A leap second is a one-second adjustment inserted into UTC (at 23:59:60 on June 30
        or December 31) to keep UTC within 0.9 seconds of UT1. The IERS announces leap seconds
        about 6 months in advance. Since 1972, 27 positive leap seconds have been inserted —
        no negative leap second has ever been needed.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📅</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Leap seconds are being abolished:</strong> In November 2022, the General
          Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) voted to discontinue leap seconds by 2035.
          UTC will be allowed to diverge from UT1 by more than 1 second for the first time.
          The maximum permitted difference will be increased to at least 1 minute. This will
          simplify timekeeping for digital infrastructure but requires updating software that
          assumes |UTC − UT1| &lt; 1 s.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Leap seconds are critically important for GNSS because each constellation handles
        them differently — some include them, some do not:
      </p>

      <div class="leap-second-table">
        <div class="lst-row lst-header">
          <span>System</span>
          <span>Leap seconds?</span>
          <span>Current offset from UTC (2024)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>TAI</strong></span>
          <span class="bad">No</span>
          <span>TAI = UTC + 37 s</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>GPS time</strong></span>
          <span class="bad">No</span>
          <span>GPS = UTC + 18 s (GPS ahead of UTC)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>Galileo time (GST)</strong></span>
          <span class="bad">No</span>
          <span>GST = GPS + 0 s (aligned to GPS at 1024 rollover epoch, Jan 1999)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>BeiDou time (BDT)</strong></span>
          <span class="bad">No</span>
          <span>BDT = UTC + 4 s (GPS − 14 s)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>GLONASS time</strong></span>
          <span class="good">Yes</span>
          <span>GLONASS = UTC(SU) + 3 hours (Moscow time)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>QZSS time</strong></span>
          <span class="bad">No</span>
          <span>QZSS = GPS time (identical)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lst-row">
          <span><strong>UTC</strong></span>
          <span class="good">Yes</span>
          <span>Reference — 37 s behind TAI as of 2024</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="gnss-time-scales">GNSS time scales</h2>
      <p>
        Each GNSS constellation maintains its own time scale, steered to UTC via its
        respective national time laboratory. The key properties:
      </p>

      <div class="gnss-times">
        <div class="gt-card gt-gps">
          <div class="gt-name">GPS Time (GPST)</div>
          <div class="gt-epoch">Epoch: 00:00:00 UTC, January 6, 1980</div>
          <div class="gt-format">Format: Week Number (WN) + Time of Week (TOW, 0–604799 s)</div>
          <div class="gt-steered">Steered to: UTC(USNO)</div>
          <div class="gt-offset">Offset: GPS = UTC + 18 s (Jan 2024)</div>
          <div class="gt-note">No leap seconds. GPS-UTC offset broadcast in subframe 4 page 18 of navigation message. Receivers must apply this to output UTC.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gt-card gt-glo">
          <div class="gt-name">GLONASS Time (GLONASST)</div>
          <div class="gt-epoch">Epoch: January 1, 1996 (start of 4-year cycle)</div>
          <div class="gt-format">Format: 4-year cycle number + day within 4-year cycle + seconds of day</div>
          <div class="gt-steered">Steered to: UTC(SU) — Russian national standard</div>
          <div class="gt-offset">Offset: GLONASST = UTC + 3 hours (Moscow Standard Time)</div>
          <div class="gt-note">GLONASS includes leap seconds — its time is continuous with UTC apart from the fixed +3h offset. This simplifies UTC conversion but differs from other constellations.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gt-card gt-gal">
          <div class="gt-name">Galileo System Time (GST)</div>
          <div class="gt-epoch">Epoch: 00:00 UTC, August 22, 1999 (GPS week 1024 rollover)</div>
          <div class="gt-format">Format: Week Number + Time of Week (same structure as GPS)</div>
          <div class="gt-steered">Steered to: UTC(BIPM) via TAI</div>
          <div class="gt-offset">Offset: GST = GPS + 0 s (nominally; actual offset &lt;50 ns)</div>
          <div class="gt-note">Designed to be interoperable with GPS. The GST-GPS offset is broadcast in the Galileo navigation message. No leap seconds.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gt-card gt-bds">
          <div class="gt-name">BeiDou Time (BDT)</div>
          <div class="gt-epoch">Epoch: 00:00 UTC, January 1, 2006</div>
          <div class="gt-format">Format: Week Number + Time of Week</div>
          <div class="gt-steered">Steered to: UTC(NTSC) — National Time Service Centre, China</div>
          <div class="gt-offset">Offset: BDT = UTC + 4 s = GPS − 14 s</div>
          <div class="gt-note">No leap seconds. The BDT-UTC offset is broadcast in the navigation message. BDT week 0 started at GPS week 1356.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="gps-time">GPS time in detail</h2>
      <p>
        GPS time is the most widely used GNSS time scale and deserves a closer look. The
        <strong>Time of Week (TOW)</strong> counts seconds from the start of the GPS week:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">GPS week starts: Saturday/Sunday midnight (00:00:00 GPS time Sunday)</div>
        <div class="formula">TOW range: 0 to 604,799 seconds (0 to 7×24×3600 − 1)</div>
        <div class="formula">TOW = 0 at: midnight Sunday GPS time (Saturday night → Sunday morning)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Example: GPS Week 2296, TOW = 388,800 s<br/>
          Day of week: 388,800 / 86,400 = 4.5 → Thursday 12:00:00 GPS time<br/>
          UTC: Thursday 12:00:00 − 18 s = Thursday 11:59:42 UTC<br/><br/>
          To compute calendar date: start from epoch (Jan 6, 1980) + (WN × 7 days) + (TOW / 86400 days)
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The navigation message broadcasts TOW in the <strong>Handover Word (HOW)</strong> at
        the start of each subframe. GPS transmits 5 subframes per 30-second frame, so the
        TOW in the HOW increments by 6 seconds (one subframe) each time.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="week-rollover">GPS week rollover</h2>
      <p>
        The GPS week number is transmitted as a 10-bit field in the legacy navigation message
        — giving a range of 0–1023, covering 1,024 weeks (~19.7 years) before rolling back to
        zero. Two rollovers have already occurred:
      </p>

      <div class="rollover-table">
        <div class="rt-row rt-header">
          <span>Rollover</span>
          <span>Date</span>
          <span>WN went from</span>
          <span>Effect</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rt-row">
          <span><strong>1st rollover</strong></span>
          <span>August 21–22, 1999</span>
          <span>1023 → 0</span>
          <span>Receivers without fix showed dates in 1980. Widely anticipated and patched.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rt-row">
          <span><strong>2nd rollover</strong></span>
          <span>April 6, 2019</span>
          <span>1023 → 0 (again)</span>
          <span>Some older receivers showed incorrect dates. Modern receivers use 13-bit WN in CNAV/CNAV-2.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="rt-row rt-future">
          <span><strong>3rd rollover</strong></span>
          <span>~November 2038</span>
          <span>1023 → 0 (legacy only)</span>
          <span>Only affects receivers using legacy L1 C/A navigation message. Modern CNAV uses 13-bit WN (valid until ~2137).</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Handling rollover in software:</strong> When parsing GPS week number from
          a legacy navigation message, always apply a rollover correction based on a known
          approximate date. A simple heuristic: if WN &lt; 500 and the current date is after
          2019, add 2048 to WN. For production software, use the CNAV message (L2C, L5) which
          carries a 13-bit WN and is rollover-safe until 2137.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="conversions">Conversion reference</h2>
      <p>
        The most common time scale conversions needed in GNSS software:
      </p>

      <div class="conversion-table">
        <div class="conv-row conv-header">
          <span>From</span>
          <span>To</span>
          <span>Formula / offset</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>GPS time</span>
          <span>UTC</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">UTC = GPST − ΔtLS   (ΔtLS = current leap seconds = 18 s, Jan 2024)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>GPS time</span>
          <span>TAI</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">TAI = GPST + 19 s   (fixed — GPS epoch was 19 s behind TAI)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>GST (Galileo)</span>
          <span>GPS time</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">GPST = GST + GGTO   (GGTO broadcast in Galileo nav msg, typically &lt;50 ns)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>BDT (BeiDou)</span>
          <span>GPS time</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">GPST = BDT + 14 s   (fixed — BDT epoch was 14 s behind GPST)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>GLONASS time</span>
          <span>UTC</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">UTC = GLONASST − 3 hours   (Moscow offset, includes leap seconds)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>GPS WN + TOW</span>
          <span>Unix timestamp</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">Unix = 315964800 + WN×604800 + TOW − ΔtLS   (315964800 = GPS epoch in Unix)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>GPS WN + TOW</span>
          <span>Julian Date</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">JD = 2444244.5 + WN×7 + TOW/86400   (2444244.5 = JD of GPS epoch)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-row">
          <span>Julian Date</span>
          <span>Modified JD</span>
          <span class="conv-formula">MJD = JD − 2400000.5   (MJD epoch = November 17, 1858)</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔧</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Practical note on ΔtLS:</strong> The GPS-UTC leap second offset ΔtLS is
          not a fixed constant — it increments every time a leap second is inserted. Always
          read ΔtLS from the navigation message (subframe 4, page 18) rather than hardcoding it.
          Using a stale ΔtLS value is a common bug in timing software that causes 1-second
          UTC errors after each leap second insertion.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚛️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">TAI is the foundation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">All precise time scales derive from TAI. TAI ticks at the SI second, has no leap seconds, and is computed from 400+ atomic clocks worldwide. GPS = TAI − 19 s (fixed).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔁</div>
          <div class="summary-title">UTC has leap seconds; GNSS mostly doesn't</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GPS, Galileo, BeiDou and QZSS do not include leap seconds. GLONASS does. Always read the GPS-UTC leap second offset from the navigation message — never hardcode it.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📅</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Each constellation has its own epoch</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GPS: Jan 6, 1980. Galileo: Aug 22, 1999. BeiDou: Jan 1, 2006. GLONASS: Jan 1, 1996 (4-year cycles). All offsets from GPS time are fixed integers except GGTO (Galileo) which is broadcast.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚠️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">GPS week rollover</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Legacy 10-bit WN rolls over every 1,024 weeks (~19.7 years). 3rd rollover: ~2038. Modern CNAV uses 13-bit WN — rollover-safe until 2137. Apply rollover correction when parsing legacy messages.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/timing/gnss-as-timing-source" class="nav-prev">← GNSS as a Timing Source</a>
        <a href="/learn/timing/timing-applications" class="nav-next">Timing Applications →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>IS-GPS-200N — GPS Interface Specification, Section 20.3.3 (UTC/GPS time relationship). <a href="https://www.navcen.uscg.gov/sites/default/files/pdf/gps/IS-GPS-200N.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAVCEN →</a></li>
          <li>BIPM — Time Department. <a href="https://www.bipm.org/en/time-faq" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">bipm.org →</a></li>
          <li>IERS — International Earth Rotation and Reference Systems Service. Leap second announcements. <a href="https://www.iers.org/IERS/EN/Science/EarthRotation/LeapSecond.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">iers.org →</a></li>
          <li>Galileo OS SIS ICD — GST-GPS time offset definition. <a href="https://www.gsc-europa.eu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GSC Europa →</a></li>
          <li>McCarthy, D. D. & Seidelmann, P. K. (2009). <em>TIME — From Earth Rotation to Atomic Physics</em>. Wiley-VCH.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout-warn { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(251,191,36,0.2); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  .formula-block { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; overflow-x: auto; }
  .formula { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 4px; line-height: 1.8; white-space: pre; }
  .formula-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.7; margin-top: 10px; }

  /* TAI facts */
  .tai-fact { display: flex; gap: 0; margin: 20px 0; background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden; }
  .tai-fact > * { flex: 1; padding: 16px; border-right: 1px solid var(--border); text-align: center; }
  .tai-fact > *:last-child { border-right: none; }
  .tf-val { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 700; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .tf-label { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.4; }

  /* Time scale relationships */
  .timescale-relationships { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .tsr-title { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .tsr-chain { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0; }
  .tsr-node { background: var(--bg3); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; padding: 14px 16px; flex: 1; }
  .tsr-tai { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); }
  .tsr-utc { border-color: rgba(0,153,255,0.3); }
  .tsr-ut1 { border-color: rgba(251,191,36,0.3); }
  .tsr-name { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .tsr-desc { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.5; }
  .tsr-arrow { display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center; justify-content: center; padding: 0 8px; min-width: 80px; }
  .tsr-offset { font-size: 10px; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 4px; text-align: center; }
  .tsr-line { width: 100%; height: 1px; background: var(--border); position: relative; }
